We are proud to be associated with the Manjara River Rejuvenation project which has resulted in alleviation of acute water shortage in Latur, a district of Maharashtra.

Under "Jal Jagruti Abhiyaan" of The Art of Living foundation, in association with Justdial, tree plantation & river bed widening was carried out for ground water retention by working closely with the local community.

After 6 long months, water flowed from taps in Latur for the first time on 1st August 2016.

Through partnership with "The Art of Living Foundation" Justdial has helped in
- De-silting of approximately 15 kilometers of river track
- Widening of river track to 80 meters width & 3 meters depth

Here is an honest take on the film 'Baankey Ki Crazy Baraat'

"Bollywood has a way of ruining compelling plot-lines with plastic acting, deep cleavages and over hyped marketing. In a sense, the Indian film theatre acts like a modern Colosseum where semi naked, muscle-carved actors entertain the vast public which crave action, sex and romance. Movies without the famous gladiators have a way of sinking to the bottom because hey, who wants to listen to an honest, well-told story?
This weekend, a bunch of new movies hit the theatre. There was the classic mega-budget super film that would make enough money to rival the national GDP of Qatar. And then there was the not-so-huge budget movie with a few familiar faces that wanted to give people a honest good laugh. As usual, the well-oiled machine of bollywood publicity, of which even the most revered film reviewers are cogs, churned out a decadent situation where the aforementioned mega-budget movie invaded the country like an unwanted virus whereas the smaller budget film grappled to take hold.
I saw the smaller budget film, Baankey ki Crazy Baraat, and was pleasantly surprised by crisp acting, excellent editing and some of the wittiest comic dialogues since the era of Hera Pheri. The direction and screenplay made me feel like I was watching a play interspersed with cinematic splendour. The plot-line was very original, unlike the usual Hollywood rip-offs that Bollywood relies upon. Perhaps the most surprising emotion I felt was a one of genuine humor. I am not a fan of Bollywood movies. I hate songs and lovey-dovey romance that only prevents the plot-line from ambling forward. I know a lot of other people like me — increasingly the Indian youth are turning to Hollywood to get their share of entertainment. But this movie was unique. It reminded me of a play because each character was deep, and this depth was visible because there was not a big movie star to blind the audience to the intricacies of the other characters. The movie highlighted issues of sexism, dysfunctional families and the all-consuming concept of the Indian marriage. Yet, it managed to stay true to its comical core, and was consistently supported by a sense of realism. The movie is a perfect addition to recently trending mid-budget, high-impact, low-star cast Bollywood movies that providing a compelling case for Indian cinema in the world.
But of-course, the critics can only write on money, and the more money they get, the more they write.
No, the movie is not set in exotic foreign locations with colorful landscapes. And no the movie does not have a massive star to help it become a money machine. But the movie does transport the average viewer to comical land of laughter. Which is a big achievement considering it didn't nearly have the same budget as the other mainstream comedy movies of recent times.
Rahul Desai, a movie critic who quit The Mumbai Mirror after being forced to change his film review on a "blockbuster", wrote that film critics can only be as good as the film produced in the country. Well obviously that's untrue. While cinema continues to get better in our country with fresh films like BKCB, the film critics cannot bother to show up on time and be brave enough to write their true sentiments."
- A Note from Sumer Vaid

QUIZ:
1. Name the Top 5 of the wealthiest people in the world.
2. Name the last 5 winners of the Ms. Universe Title.
3. Name the last 5 people who won the Nobel Prize.
How did you do?
The point is, none of us remembers the headlines of yesterday.
Even though these people must be the best in their fields...applause dies, awards are tarnished and achievements are forgotten...

Here's another quiz...let's see how this goes:
Name 5 people who helped you in times of need.
Name 5 people who taught you something worthwhile.
Name 5 people who make you feel special.
Name 5 people you enjoy spending time with.
Easier...right? :)

The people who make a difference in your life are NOT the celebs or the ones with most awards and loads of money...

Life is full of so-called ordinary people who have made the world a better place for you!

Cherish them!!!
There's so much to be thankful for!

To mark this occasion, a grand parade is held near Rajpath in New Delhi, the capital of India, beginning from Raisina Hill near the Rashtrapati Bhavan (Presidential Palace), along the Rajpath, past India Gate and on to the historic Red Fort in the old quarter of the city.

Different infantry, cavalry and mechanized regiments compose the Indian Army, the Indian Marines and the Indian Air Force's march in formation, who are decked in all their finery and official decorations.

The parade also includes many traditional dance troupes, to symbolize the cultural heritage of India. It traditionally ends with a colourful flypast by Indian Air Force jets in a tiranga formation.

You can also watch it live on TV or via Webcast @ http://republicday.nic.in/

We all recognize the Indian Flag, but how many of us know the meaning behind the design? The symbolism has been best explained by Sarvepalli Radhakrishnan, who later became India's first Vice President and second President:

"Bhagwa or the saffron colour denotes renunciation or disinterestedness. Our leaders must be indifferent to material gains and dedicate themselves to their work. The white in the centre is light, the path of truth to guide our conduct. The green shows our relation to (the) soil, our relation to the plant life here, on which all other life depends. The "Ashoka Chakra" in the centre of the white is the wheel of the law of dharma. Truth or satya, dharma or virtue ought to be the controlling principle of those who work under this flag. Again, the wheel denotes motion. There is death in stagnation. There is life in movement. India should no more resist change, it must move and go forward. The wheel represents the dynamism of a peaceful change."

The Bengal tiger can be found throughout the country except in the north-western region. It has been a national symbol of India since about the 25th century BCE when it was displayed on the Pashupati seal of the Indus Valley Civilisation. On the seal, the tiger, being the largest, represents the Yogi Shiva's people. The tiger was later the symbol of the Chola Empire from 300 CE to 1279 CE and is now designated as the official animal of India.

Times Square, New York.

Times Square is possibly one of the most famous places in the world to bring in the New Year, with hundreds of thousands attending and millions more watching on television. Watching the Waterford Crystal New Year's Eve Ball drop is an experience that any New Year reveller need to see at least once.
link_name: Best Places to bring in the New Year!

status_message:
Sydney, Australia

Join over a million people at Sydney Harbour for the absolutely stunning Midnight Fireworks show. One of the best places to see and join in the spectacular New Year celebrations is from one of the boats in the harbour.
link_name: Best Places to bring in the New Year!

status_message:
Tokyo, Japan

The Japanese really know how to bring in the New Year, with celebrations starting as early as the 29th of December and continuing all the way to the 4th of January! Fireworks, dancing, singing and lots more, the city truly comes alive.

One of the most famous New Year traditions is the Juya No Kane (The Watch-Night Bell) which rings 108 times at temples across Japan, symbolizing getting rid of all negativity.
link_name: Best Places to bring in the New Year!

India is surely a land of varied celebrations. Our growing up years were spiced up with many mythological stories and superhuman beings that fought incredible wars, epic stories of good and evil and protagonists who personified universal ideals who contributed as much to history as to the myth of this nation called India. The festival of Janmashtami is all about the jubilation over the birth of Lord Krishna and celebrates his playful and mischievous nature and symbolizes that 'Unity will lead to success eventually'. Hope the values and ideals live on forever.

Conceived as a traditional Indian palace, The Oberoi Udaivilas (ranked the best hotel in Asia and 5th in the world) showcases the rich heritage of the Mewar region of Rajasthan with its rambling courtyards, gentle rippling fountains, reflection pools and verdant gardens. Grand architecture inspired by the palaces of Rajasthan present a picture of majesty resplendent with pavilions and domes that lead you to a journey of discovery. Interiors embellished with decorative domes, hand painted frescoes, intricate mirror work and beautifully crafted artefacts create an ambience of regal splendour.

The Upahara Darshini near Netkallappa circle, Basavanagudi in Bangalore essentially started the trend of vegetarian fast food restaurants in the city. To date there are over 5000 darshinis in Bangalore serving countless meals to hundreds of thousands of people every day. Founded on the motto of serving quick meals that are simple yet wholesome; Upahara Darshini popularly known as 'UD' has earned many patrons over the years thanks to the quick, efficient service and yummy food. Simply put its a a great place for a complete breakfast, lunch or evening bite.
